Agency MCP Servers
Overview
Agency provides built-in MCP (Model Context Protocol) servers that extend your AI agent with tools for Azure DevOps, Kusto, code search, and more. There are two ways to use them:

--mcp flag — Quick, single-use configuration on the command line
MCP config — Persistent configuration in agent definitions or config files using the agency mcp command
Quick Start with --mcp
The --mcp flag on agency copilot and agency claude is the fastest way to add MCP servers to a session.

Basic Usage
Pass a built-in MCP name to enable it:

agency copilot --mcp ado
agency copilot --mcp kusto --mcp es-chat
Passing Arguments
You can pass CLI arguments to the MCP server by quoting the entire value. The arguments are the same as those available on the agency mcp <name> command.

Note
The quoting style depends on your shell. Use single quotes on macOS/Linux and double quotes on Windows.

macOS/Linux:

# Specify an ADO organization explicitly
agency copilot --mcp 'ado --organization office'

# Narrow ADO to specific toolsets
agency copilot --mcp 'ado --organization office --toolsets core,repositories,pipelines,search'

# Configure Kusto with a specific cluster
agency copilot --mcp 'kusto --service-uri https://mycluster.kusto.windows.net --database mydb'

# Use Bluebird (pass --mini for mini mode)
agency copilot --mcp 'bluebird --mini'
Windows:

# Specify an ADO organization explicitly
agency copilot --mcp "ado --organization office"

# Narrow ADO to specific toolsets
agency copilot --mcp "ado --organization office --toolsets core,repositories,pipelines,search"

# Configure Kusto with a specific cluster
agency copilot --mcp "kusto --service-uri https://mycluster.kusto.windows.net --database mydb"

# Use Bluebird (pass --mini for mini mode)
agency copilot --mcp "bluebird --mini"
Run agency mcp <name> --help to see the available options for each MCP server.

Aliasing for Multiple Instances
To use the same MCP server multiple times with different configurations, prefix the value with an alias:

macOS/Linux:

agency copilot \
  --mcp 'ado_office: ado --organization office' \
  --mcp 'ado_mseng: ado --organization mseng'
Windows:

agency copilot ^
  --mcp "ado_office: ado --organization office" ^
  --mcp "ado_mseng: ado --organization mseng"
This creates two separate ADO MCP server instances, each connecting to a different organization. Without an alias, the MCP name is used as the key, and a second --mcp ado would override the first.

