MCP Config Resolution
When you run agency copilot or agency claude, Agency reads MCP server configurations from multiple sources and merges them before passing the result to the underlying engine. When two sources define the same MCP name, the higher-priority source wins.

Priority	Source	Description
1 (lowest)	Global defaults	Bluebird is included automatically when in an ADO repository
2	~/.copilot/mcp-config.json	User-level global config
3	Agency config	agency.toml / agency.yaml files (global, org, or project-level)
4	Agent frontmatter	mcp-servers defined in the loaded agent's YAML
5 (highest)	--mcp CLI flag	MCP servers specified on the command line
Note
.vscode/mcp.json is no longer read during MCP resolution. The first time you run agency copilot or agency claude in a repository that has this file, Agency offers a one-time migration to move servers into the repository's Agency config file (typically agency.toml). After migration, Agency config is the recommended place for repository-level MCP configuration. VS Code itself continues to read .vscode/mcp.json for its own MCP support — do not delete the file if VS Code still needs it.

For example, if agency.toml defines an ado MCP and you also pass --mcp 'ado --organization office' (macOS/Linux) or --mcp "ado --organization office" (Windows), the CLI flag takes precedence and the agency.toml entry is overridden.

Note
MCPs are loaded once at session start. If you modify a config file during a session, restart the session for changes to take effect.

Configuring MCPs in Config Files
Beyond the --mcp flag, you can configure MCP servers persistently in config files. These files are read by Agency during resolution (see above) and are also read directly by the underlying engines (Copilot CLI, Claude Code, VS Code).

Agency Config — Recommended
The recommended way to persistently enable MCP servers is through Agency config files (agency.toml or agency.yaml). These files are layered — you can define MCPs globally (~/.agency/), per-org, or per-project, and values in closer files override distant ones.

Set via CLI (easiest):

Note
Use single quotes on macOS/Linux and double quotes on Windows when passing arguments to --mcp.

macOS/Linux:

# Add an MCP to your project config
agency config set --mcp ado

# Add with arguments
agency config set --mcp 'kusto --service-uri https://mycluster.kusto.windows.net --database mydb'

# Add globally (applies to all repos)
agency config set --global --mcp icm

# Add multiple MCPs with an alias
agency config set --mcp ado --mcp 'ado_office: ado --organization office'
Windows:

# Add an MCP to your project config
agency config set --mcp ado

# Add with arguments
agency config set --mcp "kusto --service-uri https://mycluster.kusto.windows.net --database mydb"

# Add globally (applies to all repos)
agency config set --global --mcp icm

# Add multiple MCPs with an alias
agency config set --mcp ado --mcp "ado_office: ado --organization office"
Or edit the config file directly:

agency.toml:

[mcps.builtins.ado]
type = "ado"

[mcps.builtins.ado_office]
type = "ado"
organization = "office"
toolsets = ["core", "repositories", "pipelines", "search"]

[mcps.builtins.kusto]
type = "kusto"
service-uri = "https://mycluster.kusto.windows.net"
database = "mydb"
agency.yaml:

mcps:
  builtins:
    ado:
      type: ado
    ado_office:
      type: ado
      organization: office
      toolsets: [core, repositories, pipelines, search]
    kusto:
      type: kusto
      service-uri: https://mycluster.kusto.windows.net
      database: mydb
Run agency mcp <name> --help to see the available options for each MCP server. See Agency Config for full details on config file discovery and layering.

Note
The JSON key for MCP servers differs by config format. Agency accepts all variants (servers, mcpServers, mcp-servers) for flexibility, but you should use the convention expected by the engine that reads the file natively.

.vscode/mcp.json — Legacy Repository Config (Migrated Automatically)
Important
.vscode/mcp.json is no longer read by Agency at runtime. The first time you run agency copilot or agency claude in a repository that has this file, Agency offers a one-time migration wizard to move servers into the repository's Agency config file (typically agency.toml). Use Agency config for new repository-level MCP configuration. Note that VS Code itself still reads .vscode/mcp.json for its own MCP support, so do not delete the file if VS Code needs it.

If your repository still has a .vscode/mcp.json, it uses the "servers" key:

{
  "servers": {
    "ado": {
      "command": "agency",
      "args": ["mcp", "ado", "--organization", "myorg"]
    },
    "kusto": {
      "command": "agency",
      "args": [
        "mcp",
        "kusto",
        "--service-uri",
        "https://mycluster.kusto.windows.net"
      ]
    }
  }
}
~/.copilot/mcp-config.json — User Global Config
Place an mcp-config.json file at ~/.copilot/mcp-config.json for MCP servers you want available in all sessions:

{
  "mcpServers": {
    "kusto": {
      "command": "agency",
      "args": [
        "mcp",
        "kusto",
        "--service-uri",
        "https://mycluster.kusto.windows.net"
      ]
    }
  }
}
Agent Frontmatter — Agent-Level Config
Add mcpServers to your agent YAML frontmatter. The command and args fields reference the agency mcp command:

---
name: ado-agent
description: Manages Azure DevOps work items and pull requests
mcpServers:
  ado:
    type: local
    command: agency
    args: ["mcp", "ado", "--organization", "myorg"]
    tools: ["*"]
---
You are an Azure DevOps specialist. Use the ADO MCP tools to help users.
See MCP Servers in Custom Agents for full details on agent-level MCP configuration, tool restrictions, and server types.

The agency mcp Command
The agency mcp <name> command launches individual MCP servers as stdio processes. This is the command you reference when configuring MCP servers in config files.

agency mcp <COMMAND>

Commands:
  ado               Launch Azure DevOps MCP server
  kusto             Launch Azure Kusto MCP server
  bluebird          Launch Engineering Copilot MCP server
  icm               Launch ICM MCP server
  security-context  Azure Security Context MCP
  es-chat           Launch ES Chat MCP server
  msft-learn        Launch Microsoft Learn MCP server
  workiq            Launch WorkIQ MCP server
  teams             Launch Microsoft Teams MCP server
  mail              Launch Microsoft Mail MCP server
  calendar          Launch Microsoft Calendar MCP server
  cloudbuild        Launch CloudBuild MCP server
  word              Launch Microsoft Word MCP server
  planner           Launch Microsoft Planner MCP server
  m365-user         Launch Microsoft Graph user MCP server
  m365-copilot      Launch M365 Copilot search MCP server
